(both Devon), Norley Farm in Wonersh (Surrey), and Norley in Calne (Wilts). Most of the place-names derive from Middle English  <i>north</i> ‘north, northern’ +  <i>ley</i> ‘woodland clearing, glade’, also ‘open land’, or Old English  <i>norð</i> ‘north, northern’ +  <i>lēah</i> ‘open woodland’. Northleigh by Honiton (Devon) was recorded simply as  <i>Legh</i> in 1228, with  <i>North-</i> added later to distinguish it from nearby Southleigh."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Norley was born about 1275, in Norley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thurstan Norleigh. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1275–":"umbes 1275–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1305":"1305","1333":"1333","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","about 1275":"umbes 1275","Norley, Cheshire, England":"Norley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1275–":"noin 1275–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1305–1333":"1305–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1333":"1333","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","about 1275":"noin 1275","Norley, Cheshire, England":"Norley, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1275–":"environ 1275–Décédé","1275–Ma